{"title_page": "Mathias James O'Conway", "text_new": "'''Mathias James O'Conway''', aka '''Matha \u00d3 Conmhai''' (3 February 1766 &ndash; 28 November 1842) was a [[linguist]] and [[lexicographer]].\n\n==Life==\nO'Conway was born in Galway town to Matthias O'Conway, said to have been a town merchant, and his wife, Isabel Ni hOg\u00e1in. He had an older brother, Se\u00e1n ('John)'. A Gaeilgeoir (native Irish speaker), \u00d3 Conmhai only learned English from age eight upon attending the [[Augustinians|Augustinian]] school in the town. By his own account he first became intrigued with languages upon coming into contact with [[Jewish]] [[refugee]]s from [[Gibraltar]] when he was aged about fourteen, about 1780. Following a street fracas in [[Dublin]] in early 1783 \u00d3 Conmhai was obliged to leave Ireland, never to return.\n\nHe first settled in [[Grenada]] in the [[Caribbean]]; by April 1784 he was living in [[Philadelphia]].  He became a member of the Pennsylvania [[militia]], and was posted to the territory of the [[Seneca people|Seneca]], learning elements of  \"three of their languages.\"\n\nHe married Rebecca Archer of Carlisle, Penn., who was the American-born daughter of an Irish couple. Their first child, Ceclia, was born in December 1787 by which time he set himself up as a schoolteacher in [[Pittsburgh]]. The couple would have nine children, eight of who survived childhood, two sons dying young in [[Latin America]].\n\nO'Conway worked for decades on several monumental philological works, but much was unpublished. Some of his papers were lost, but a great deal survives in the [[National Library of Ireland]], Dublin. They show awareness of the works of Bishop John O'Brien and [[Aodh Buidhe Mac Cruitin]], but clearly contains his own independent research and conclusions.\n\n<blockquote>\n''\"O'Conway was almost certainly the first person to write and publish language-learning books in the United States. One of these, his \"Hispano-Anglo grammar\" (1810), was a grammar of Spanish for the English speaker and also a book of dialogues and topical vocabulary lists of everyday use. ... O'Conway's life and work thus await serious study from those who can evaluate hhis contribution to the evolution of linguistics and language teaching in the United States and his place in the history of Irish and indeed Spanish lexicography.\"''\n</blockquote>\n\n==References==\n* ''Dictionary of Irish Biography: From The Earliest Times to the Year 2002:volume 7, Oates - Patten'' ed. James McGuire and James Quinn, pp.&nbsp;317\u2013319.\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oconway, Mathias James}}\n[[Category:Linguists from Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish lexicographers]]\n[[Category:People from County Galway]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:1766 births]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish-language writers]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Ireland emigrants to the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Irish scholars and academics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mathias James O'Conway''', aka '''Matha \u00d3 Conmhai''' (3 February 1766 &ndash; 28 November 1842) was a [[linguist]] and [[lexicographer]].\n\n==Life==\nO'Conway was born in Galway town to Matthias O'Conway, said to have been a town merchant, and his wife, Isabel Ni hOg\u00e1in. He had an older brother, Se\u00e1n ('John)'. A Gaeilgeoir (native Irish speaker), \u00d3 Conmhai only learned English from age eight upon attending the [[Augustinian]] school in the town. By his own account he first became intrigued with languages upon coming into contact with [[Jewish]] [[refugee]]s from [[Gibraltar]] when he was aged about fourteen, about 1780. Following a street fracas in [[Dublin]] in early 1783 \u00d3 Conmhai was obliged to leave Ireland, never to return.\n\nHe first settled in [[Grenada]] in the [[Caribbean]]; by April 1784 he was living in [[Philadelphia]].  H